The nationâ€™s leading first aid charity.
Every year, more than 400,000 people learn how to save a life through our training programmes.
Our volunteers provide first aid in their communities and thanks to them fewer lives will be lost needlessly. 
Raise money. Help save lives. Be the difference.
charity.name: St John Ambulance
eventName: Share Your Sparkle - SJA National Welcome Team Gets Festive
story:
As a charity with a long history of serving humanity, we are proud of our past, our role in the pandemic and excited about creating a healthier, safer, brighter and more resilient future.

This winter may be our toughest yet and I am helping to bring some community spirit by sharing my sparkle by supporting St John. St John volunteers treat and transport thousands of patients each year, and in times of crisis we are England's national health reserve.

During the pandemic our skilled and highly trained volunteers are working long shifts supporting sick people and their families, in hospitals, in ambulances and at home. We are proud to be working alongside the nations ambulance trusts and in hospitals around the country.

"I enjoy helping people and its what I have been training to do. Its very rewarding personally knowing that my colleagues and I are making a difference to peoples lives when they most need it." Tom Willis, volunteer.

As part of the big St John Ambulance family, we, as the National Welcome Team, want to join in with the festive spirit, share our sparkle whilst volunteering, and hopefully helping to raise support and awareness for this vital cause.

Will you support me and help make a difference?

story:
Thanks for visiting my page.Â 

On one fairly drunken Zoom quiz night, the family made a pact to make the year of 2021 a year of charity fundraising challenges.Â  Some team members are swimming 8k in open water, some are skydiving, some are walking the Yorkshire 3 peaks and some are doing more than one event.Â 

I am running a whopping 874 miles from Land's End to John O' Groats, virtually through Endtoend Limited, in 12 months, but I do aim to beat that.

I started on November 22nd 2020 and aim to finish before November 21st 2021.

We have all experienced a difficult 2020, with family members touched with heart complications so with this in mind, we decided that 2021 would be time for family and fundraising.

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. Â£24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
Help us raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas! 

During December hundreds of our fundraising dogs across the UK would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at supermarket and street collections, Christmas fairs and festive coffee mornings. Our four-legged fundraisers support the 400+ fundraising groups across the UK from Glasgow to Plymouth and everywhere in between.

Due to the current situation, most of our fundraising groups will not be out collecting this festive season, and our four-legged fundraisers will be very much missed! We hope you will do your bit and help us as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships! Heres how you can join in: 

	Donate Â£12 and share our posts across social media nominating a friend, family member or colleague to  get involved

	Set up your own fundraiser on this page

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation.

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss.

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society.

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

story:
Hi, I'm Svenja. I've had a pretty rough time for the last 13 months - to say that life hasn't been kind would be an understatement, and I have felt overwhelmed and torn apart to the point of physical and mental breakdowns, including a suicide attempt at the end of last year.Â 

While starting to recover mentally and physically, Covid and the isolation associated with that made the recovery from depression a big struggle, my criminal freeholder putting me through hell didn't help either, but I got back on my feet, returned to work and finally felt some sense of achievement again.

However, recent bad news in my immediate family directly related to this fundraiser pushed me over the edge and accumulated in a complete meltdown earlier this week. I don't know what happened Tuesday morning except passing out in my bedroom while blasting out a Wildhearts album at volume 55. If it hadn't been for my friend ringing me relentlessly and making me come out for a walk in nature, I don't know what would have happened. So I've decided it's time to turn things around and fight back by making myself stronger.....so I can be strong for those who need me.Â 

While I'm dedicating this to my grandad Paul Brecht, who was taken by cancer way too soon at the age of 69 (when I was 17), I am doing this for close family members and friends who have either recently undergone cancer treatment or are going through it at this very moment - and those we've lost along the way. You know who you are, and I will muster up the strength to do this in the hope that it will give you the strength to beat this. I am not mentioning names out of respect for privacy, but if you express your wish to be named here, I will do so.

I'll have to reactivate my Facebook account to share this (so yes, I apologise in advance for any uncontrolled and uncensored rants about my freeholder, Covid and Brexit featuring the brightest rainbow of swear words known to mankind), but I'm mainly reactivating the account for this.

Â "Oh please, not another fundraiser!" I hear some of you say, but this one is closer to my heart than it could possibly be. And to show how much it means to me, I will give something back in return. Anyone making a donation of Â£10 or more will receive a glossy photo print (you can choose any one of my nature/sunset/whatever pics on FB), anyone making a donation of Â£25 or more will receive a handmade piece of vegan soap and a photo print, and any donation of Â£50 or more will receive a professionally printed calendar for 2022 (you can either choose your favourite photos or I'll put a nice selection together for you). If any of those making Â£25/Â£50 donations are fans of Darrell's music, you can also choose a Darrell shirt or CD instead (or a calendar with high quality photos of Darrell). The first Â£50 donation from a Darrell fan can have the one and only "Rockin' The Streets" hoodie (size XL). The only small print: I can only cover postage within the UK for these gifts - I can post overseas, but would kindly ask you to cover the excess postage.

Please take this journey with me - I'll do the walking and provide the photos (some days might be too rainy for pics, but I promise to capture all things beautiful when the sun is out), and you can motivate me - and bring hope to those close to me.

I need to do this to turn things around. It's too easy to drown in fear, sorrow and grief while being ripped to shreds by my freeholder - I will not let them win....instead, I want to help my loved ones and, at the end of the day, help myself back on my feet because the last 13 months have quite frankly knocked me off my feet....so I will use those very feet and walk and walk and walk.

Thank you in advance from the bottom of my heart,

Svenja xxx

(P.S. for the photos, soap, calendars etc. please allow some time, as I have to get them printed and/or make the soap. Darrell merch is available instantly. I have asked his permission and he is happy to support this cause.)

As most of you all know Cancer is a big life changer and killer in our life time,Â whether it is a friend or loved one that has contracted this terrible illness. Â I for one have lost a loved one to this, being my Grandmother. It was a painful and heart breaking experience for me and my family to deal with.Â Â The doctors and nurses who took care of my Nan during her difficult and scary timeÂ made things more comfortable for her last days.Â I would like to take this opportunity to do my bit to give a little back. Â 

So with your help no matter how great or small I can help fund the research that goes into this terrible disease.Â 

Thanks againÂ 

JaneÂ x

pageSummary: Taking part in the Reading University 3 Peaks Trek because They are a fantastic charity
pageSummaryWhat: Taking part in the Reading University 3 Peaks Trek
story:
Story

On the 15th June 2021, I will be taking on the challenge of climbing theÂ  3 highest peaks in the UK (Ben Nevis, Scafell Pike and Snowdon) in 36 hours. I will be doing this with a team from the University of Reading, in collaboration with the tour provider Choose a Challenge, to raise money for the wonderful Marie Curie Charity. Throughout the year I will be training, fundraising, and keeping up to date with all the work Marie Curie are doing.

The Marie Curie is a charity who provideÂ care and support through terminal illness. They help those living with anyÂ terminal illness, and their families, offering expert care, guidance, andÂ support right from diagnosis through to bereavement. Their aim is to ensureÂ patients have the best quality of life and can keep independence and dignityÂ for as long as possible. They have 9 hospices across the UK and have anÂ information and support line that they have recently extended from 5 to 7 daysÂ a week.

For a little more information on the Marie Curie, have a
look through their website:

https://www.mariecurie.org.uk

Donations will be hugely appreciated, and I look forward to
all that this year has in store! A big thank you in advance and I look forward to updating you on my journey.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.


Rather than flowers at Dad's funeral, Kate, I and the family would prefer if a donation to Marie Curie was made because quite simply without their support, we would have been unable to have given Dad his final wish; to be nursed at home through his last few weeks.Â Â Â 

The ladies would arrive at 10 pm and sit with dad until 7 am, latterly up to 3 times a week so that we could rest and sleep.
My Dad was an amazing, kind and unselfish man who was loved and cherished by so many. He led a full and happy life and celebrated his 90th birthday in August of this year. Cancer took his life finally on December 10th 2020

RNLI crews and lifeguards have saved over 142,700 lives since 1824 but weâ€™re more than a rescue service.Â 

RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour rescue service in the UK and Ireland, and their seasonal lifeguards look after people on busy beaches. Their Flood Rescue Team helps those affected by flooding.Â They influence, supervise and educate peopleÂ  throughout the UK and their international teams work with like-minded organisations to help tackle drowning in communities at risk all around the world.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Thank you visiting my Just Giving page. 

RNLI lifeboats in the South West protect hundreds of communities through their 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
The stunning coastline of Cornwall, Devon, Dorset, Somerset, Isles of Scilly and the Channel Islands are enjoyed by millions of people from across the country every year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

The RNLI relies on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea.

Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate.
